<TEXT>
<P>
American arms sales to the Third World in 1988 rose by 66% from the year before 
while Soviet sales fell by 47% during the same period, the Congressional 
Research Service said, according to the New York Times. The newspaper said U.S. 
sales to the Third World previously had lagged far behind the those of the 
Soviet Union. U. S. sales in 1988 reached $9.2 billion compared to $9.9 billion 
for Moscow. U.S. and Soviet sales account for nearly two-thirds of all arms 
sales to developing countries. 
