</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Blazes whipped by hot, dry winds have destroyed nearly 20,000 acres of forest 
and brushland in California, fire officials said. One of the worst of the 
fires, an 11,700-acre blaze about 45 miles northeast of Fresno in the central 
Sierra Nevada foothills, was nearly contained. The arson-caused fire destroyed 
seven houses and forced about 2,500 people from their homes for a time. A 
5,700-acre wildfire in the Cleveland National Forest continued to burn out of 
control in a remote area of San Diego County. About 900 firefighters saved 13 
homes and structures. 
