<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: VALVANO'S PROGRAM COMES UNDER ATTACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jim Valvano should choose between his role as athletic director-basketball 
coach at North Carolina State and his outside interests, said Hugh Fuller, 
director of the school's academic tutoring program. 
</P>
<P>
In an interview published Monday by the News and Observer of Raleigh, Fuller 
also said that: 
</P>
<P>
 -- Academic tutors hired by the athletic department did course work for 
basketball players, who then submitted it as their own. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Athletic department officials abused policies that allow students to 
withdraw for medical or psychological reasons in order to keep players 
academically eligible. 
</P>
<P>
 -- School officials persuaded instructors to give players who were in academic 
trouble incompletes, rather than failing grades, allowing the players to remain 
eligible. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Top university officials ordered one star basketball player reinstated to a 
study hall after the player had been kicked out for disrupting other students. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Players were steered toward courses taught by sympathetic instructors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
