<HEADLINE>
<P>
DRUG-ALCOHOL COMPACT SIGNED BY 7 STATES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The governors of seven states have agreed to cooperate in developing programs 
to combat drug and alcohol abuse. 
</P>
<P>
The Middle Atlantic Governors' Compact on Drug and Alcohol Abuse was signed 
Sunday in a ceremony during the National Governors' Assn. Conference by the 
governors of Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Virginia and West 
Virginia. Earlier, it had been signed by New York Gov. Mario M. Cuomo. 
</P>
<P>
The pact commits the states to a comprehensive regional project of 
information-sharing and training, developing a coordinated approach to drug 
abuse problems and methods in prevention and early intervention. 
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the participating governors said that later this week, District 
of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry also is expected to join the pact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
