<HEADLINE>
<P>
'GIVE US PROOF,' WIFE OF COL. HIGGINS TELLS CAPTORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Robin Higgins called on her husband's captors today to "give us proof" of 
whether he is dead or alive. 
</P>
<P>
Robin Higgins, out of the public eye at the Pentagon, repeated through a 
spokeswoman that she had viewed the videotape of the purported execution of her 
husband, Lt. Col. William R. Higgins. 
</P>
<P>
However, she said, "It is impossible to make a definite determination on 
whether my husband is dead or alive." 
</P>
<P>
However, several Pentagon officials interviewed privately said they are acting 
on the assumption that the tape did show Higgins. 
</P>
<P>
"Quite a few of us believe he's gone," said one official, who spoke on 
condition he not be identified by name. 
</P>
<P>
The official said Robin Higgins has been "holding up well. She's a very strong 
person." 
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokeswoman Army Maj. Kathy Wood relayed the comments from Robin 
Higgins. 
</P>
<P>
"I want my husband returned home," Robin Higgins was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
She also called on his captors to "give us proof of his condition," Wood said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
